	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">kshin981 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">You are missing the point. Mirroring is not just a software issue. It DOES require extra wiring in actual hareware, at minimum. Because of this, mirrored chip and non mirrored chip is, however slight the difference is, HARDWARE-wisly different, . It is not a HACK to creat a new mappers for the hardware-wisly different chip, but was just a matter of convinience to merge similar hardwares into one mapper.</div>I'm not missing any point. Mirroring does does not require extra wiring, it's a consequence of partial decoding, ie ignoring high address lines. Technically this is less wiring than a "standard" cart. There is already a mapper for NROM-like boards: mapper 0.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I'm just saying that since we now have a certain type of chip that is not working under currunt system, let's create another mapper and wait for the emu authors to apply them.  I don't understand why you are calling this as a HACKY approach.</div>Certain type of chip? It's just an 8K ROM and it DOES work under the current system. Instead of just using a 16K PRG ROM image (mirrored), which should be in turn mirrored again by the emulator, you want to implement another NROM mapper specifically to detect malformed ROMs of a specific size. I call that a hack since it modifies the standard behavior of the PRG block count. Perhaps 8K ROMs should have been considered by the iNES format, but also perhaps there are unlimited shortcomings of iNES and it's silly to just now crusade over one one that has been known forever and is easily ignored since it affects nothing.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
