	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">That is a side effect of using the wrong hardware. If you had an 8kB ROM there would be no top-most address lines to need to connect.<br /></div>
<br />
<br />Rom-wisely, you are right, but the CPU still has A11 ~ A15 which is connected to the P1(catridge slot) of NES. The catridge must have some form of wiring to handle those address lines, such as making them an open field, hardwiring to the ground, and so force...
<br />
<br />Since this unneeded lines(A15 has actual use as a PRG/CE) are still accepted and handled by the rom chip set, I consider this as a mapper information. 
<br />
<br />And, if one type of mapper information cannot be handled by the currunt mappers, then what is wrong with creating another mapper to handle them? If some already-existing mapper can incorporate a new mapper information, surely we can merge this to the already-exising mapper for the convinience and to spare mappers for future use.
<br />
<br />But we all know that the 8kB chips are, due to iNes header limitation, very difficult to be handled by mapper 0. So I'm saying let's creat new mapper for it and all the problem will be solved with the least affort possible. I just don't understand why this approch are being attacked as "a Hack" by a certain person.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
